    text: `In the third century BC, in the Egyptian city of Alexandria, an institution arose with an ambition never before attempted: to collect every book in the world. The Library of Alexandria became antiquity's greatest center of learning — and its loss remains history's most lamented intellectual catastrophe.

Founded under the Ptolemaic dynasty, the Greek rulers of Egypt after Alexander the Great, the library pursued acquisition with extraordinary aggression. According to ancient accounts, ships docking at Alexandria's harbor were searched, and any scrolls aboard were confiscated and copied; the library kept the originals and returned the copies. Agents traveled the Mediterranean purchasing texts. At its height, the collection may have held hundreds of thousands of scrolls — encompassing Greek literature, Egyptian records, Babylonian astronomy, Buddhist texts, and Hebrew scriptures.

The library was more than a warehouse of scrolls. Attached to it was the Mouseion, a research institution where salaried scholars lived, dined together, and worked. The roster of minds associated with Alexandria reads like a founding faculty of Western science: Euclid composed his Elements of geometry there. Eratosthenes calculated the circumference of the Earth with astonishing accuracy using shadows and geometry. Herophilus conducted pioneering studies of human anatomy. Aristarchus proposed, seventeen centuries before Copernicus, that the Earth orbits the sun.

What destroyed it? Popular legend blames a single great fire, but historians describe something less dramatic and more unsettling: a slow decline spanning centuries. Julius Caesar's forces accidentally burned part of the collection in 48 BC. Later emperors cut funding and persecuted scholars. Civil wars damaged the district where the library stood. By the time of the Arab conquest in the seventh century — often wrongly blamed for the destruction — the great library had effectively ceased to exist long before.

The deeper lesson lies in that slowness. Knowledge, the library's fate suggests, is rarely destroyed in a single spectacular blaze. It is lost through neglect — budget by budget, scholar by scholar, generation by generation — whenever a civilization decides that preserving what it knows is no longer worth the cost.`,
