    text: `Here is a classic puzzle. A pond contains a single lily pad that doubles in size every day. On day thirty, the pond is completely covered. On which day was the pond half covered? Intuition whispers "day fifteen." The correct answer is day twenty-nine. If that surprises you, you have just experienced the cognitive blind spot that makes epidemics so dangerous.

Infectious diseases spread, at least initially, through exponential growth: each infected person infects several others, who each infect several more. Epidemiologists capture this with a number called R — the average number of people infected by each case. When R is two, one case becomes two, then four, then eight. The numbers seem trivial for weeks: ten cases, twenty, forty. Human intuition, trained on linear change, reads this as a minor problem. Then, with the inevitability of the lily pond, the curve explodes — a thousand, ten thousand, a hundred thousand — and hospitals that seemed comfortably empty are overwhelmed within days.

This mathematical structure explains the most counterintuitive feature of epidemic response: measures must be taken while they still appear unnecessary. Restrictions imposed when hospitals are already full come four or five doubling-times too late; the patients who will fill the next two weeks of beds are already infected. Public health officials thus face a cruel paradox, sometimes called the preparedness trap: if early action succeeds, the disaster never materializes, and the response is condemned as an overreaction. Success looks like wasted effort.

The mathematics also offers genuine hope, because exponents work in both directions. R is not a fixed property of a virus; it is a product of biology and behavior. Vaccination, masks, ventilation, and reduced contact each shave a fraction from R. Push R below one — even slightly — and the epidemic does not merely slow; it decays exponentially, each generation of infection smaller than the last.

The lily pond, run backwards, empties as quickly as it filled. The challenge is not mathematical but psychological: learning to trust the curve before our eyes can see it.`,
