    text: `My grandfather kept a diary for sixty-one years. After his death, we found them in his closet: sixty-one identical notebooks, one per year, filled with small, disciplined handwriting. I expected profound reflections. Instead, I found entries like this: "Rain in the morning. Fixed the fence. Tomatoes coming along well. Keiko made curry."

At first, I was disappointed. Then, over months of reading, I came to understand that I was holding something more valuable than philosophy.

The entries, trivial individually, accumulated into something extraordinary: a complete, honest texture of a human life. Great events appeared — weddings, births, the deaths of friends — but they occupied the same modest space as the weather and the tomatoes. This, I realized, is how life is actually lived. Not as a highlight reel, but as thousands of ordinary days, each one mostly forgotten. His diary refused to forget them.

Psychologists have documented what diarists have long known intuitively: writing about daily experience changes our relationship with it. The act of converting experience into sentences forces a kind of processing — vague feelings must become specific words, and in that conversion, they often lose their power to overwhelm. Expressive writing has been linked in studies to reduced stress and even modest improvements in immune function. The diary is the cheapest therapist in the world.

But the deeper function may be the one my grandfather's notebooks performed: the defeat of time's compression. Memory ruthlessly summarizes. Entire years collapse into a few retained scenes, and we lose the truth that every era of our lives — including the ones we now romanticize — was composed mostly of unremarkable Tuesdays. A diary preserves the Tuesdays. Reading them back, one discovers that happiness rarely lived where memory claims it did. It lived in the fixed fence, the developing tomatoes, the curry.

I started my own notebook in April. Most entries are embarrassingly dull, which I have decided is precisely the point.

Tonight's entry: "Cold. Studied math. Mom made stew. Wrote this."

Sixty years to go.`,
