    text: `Your phone performs a small miracle every time you open a map: it determines your position on a planet of five hundred million square kilometers to within a few meters. The system behind this — GPS — is a story of satellites, atomic clocks, and, unexpectedly, Einstein.

The Global Positioning System consists of about thirty satellites orbiting twenty thousand kilometers above Earth. Each satellite continuously broadcasts a deceptively simple message: its own position, and the precise time the message was sent. Your phone receives these signals and performs an elegant calculation. Radio waves travel at the speed of light, so the delay between transmission and arrival reveals the distance to each satellite. Knowing your distance from one satellite places you somewhere on a vast sphere; from two satellites, on a circle; from three, at one of two points — and a fourth signal resolves both the ambiguity and your receiver's clock error.

The entire scheme depends on almost unimaginable timing precision. Light travels thirty centimeters in one nanosecond — a billionth of a second — so a clock error of one microsecond would scatter your position by three hundred meters. GPS satellites therefore carry atomic clocks, stable to about one second in three million years.

Here the story takes its remarkable turn. According to Einstein's relativity, time itself does not flow uniformly. Satellites race along at fourteen thousand kilometers per hour, which slows their clocks slightly relative to ours. Simultaneously, they orbit far from Earth's mass, where weaker gravity makes their clocks run faster. The two effects partially cancel, but a net difference remains: satellite clocks gain about thirty-eight microseconds per day. Trivial? Without correction, GPS positions would drift by roughly ten kilometers every day, rendering the system useless within hours. Engineers must deliberately adjust the satellite clocks to compensate.

Consider what this means. Every time your phone guides you to a restaurant, it quietly confirms one of the strangest discoveries in the history of physics: time runs differently in the sky than on the ground — and we have built our daily convenience upon that strangeness.`,
