    text: `The ancient Greeks preserved the ship of the hero Theseus as a monument. As planks rotted, they were replaced with new timber — one by one, year after year — until eventually no original piece remained. Plutarch, recording the story two thousand years ago, posed the question that philosophers have argued about ever since: is it still the same ship?

If your instinct says yes — identity survives gradual replacement — the philosopher Thomas Hobbes prepared a trap. Suppose someone collected every discarded original plank and reassembled them into a complete ship. Now two vessels stand in the harbor: one with perfect continuity but no original parts, another with all original parts but no continuity. Which is the ship of Theseus? Both have a claim. They cannot both be the same ship — can they?

The puzzle would be a charming curiosity if it stayed in the harbor. It does not. You are the ship.

The cells of your body are continuously replaced — your skin every few weeks, your red blood cells every few months, the lining of your stomach every few days. The atoms composing you today are overwhelmingly not the atoms that composed you a decade ago. The eight-year-old whose photograph sits in your family's album shares almost no physical material with you, holds different beliefs, different memories, different fears. By what right do you claim to be that child?

Philosophers have proposed various rescues. Perhaps identity resides not in material but in pattern — the organization persists while components flow through it, as a river remains "the same river" though its water is never the same. Perhaps identity lies in continuity of memory, each stage linked to the next like an unbroken chain. Perhaps — the most unsettling option — strict identity over time is simply an illusion, a convenient fiction stitched together by memory and a name.

There is no agreed answer. The ship sails on, plank by replaced plank, carrying everyone who has ever looked at an old photograph and said, without hesitation, "That's me."`,
