    desc: "消滅の危機にある言語を考える読み物。言語多様性の価値。",
    text: `Roughly seven thousand languages are spoken on Earth today. By the most cited estimates, half of them may fall silent within this century. Somewhere in the world, approximately every few months, a language loses its last fluent speaker — and with one quiet death, an entire way of describing reality vanishes.

Languages rarely die suddenly. The process follows a recognizable pattern, unfolding across three generations. The grandparents speak the ancestral language fluently. The parents understand it but answer in the dominant language — the language of schools, jobs, television, and opportunity. The children acquire only fragments: food words, terms of affection, perhaps a song. The language retreats from the marketplace to the kitchen, from the kitchen to memory, and finally to the archive.

The forces driving this are seldom mysterious and rarely voluntary in any meaningful sense. Economic pressure makes the dominant language the price of employment. Historical policies were often more direct: in boarding schools across North America and Australia, indigenous children were punished for speaking their mother tongues. Parents who experienced such punishment frequently chose not to transmit the language — an act of protection that completed, with love, what policy had begun with force.

What exactly is lost when a language dies? Not merely vocabulary. Each language encodes generations of accumulated knowledge: which plants heal, how weather signals read, how kinship obligations bind a community together. Languages also embody distinct cognitive maps — some encode direction by compass points rather than left and right, producing speakers with extraordinary spatial orientation; others grammatically mark how a speaker knows what they claim, building evidence into every sentence. Each loss narrows the recorded range of what human minds have invented.

Yet the story is not uniformly grim. Hebrew, effectively unspoken in daily life for centuries, was revived into the mother tongue of millions. Welsh, Maori, and Hawaiian have clawed back ground through immersion schools and determined communities. Smartphone keyboards and streaming media, once engines of linguistic homogenization, now host apps teaching endangered tongues.

A language survives exactly as long as parents speak it to children. Every revival begins with that single, stubborn act.`,
