    text: `Consider the inventory of your daily life: search engines, video platforms, social networks, messaging apps, maps, email. Services that would have seemed miraculous a generation ago, delivered to billions of people, apparently free of charge. Yet the companies providing them rank among the most valuable enterprises in human history. The contradiction dissolves once you understand a now-famous principle: when the product is free, you are the product.

More precisely, your attention is. The dominant business model of the consumer internet is a three-sided trade. Platforms provide services to users at no monetary cost. Users provide attention and behavioral data. Advertisers pay the platform for precisely targeted access to that attention. The arrangement is not new in spirit — broadcast television ran on the same logic for decades — but the precision is unprecedented. Where a TV network knew roughly that homemakers watched afternoon dramas, a modern platform may infer your location history, purchasing intentions, emotional vulnerabilities, and political leanings, often with unsettling accuracy.

This model has a structural consequence that explains much about the modern internet: the platform's revenue scales with the time you spend, not with the benefit you receive. An app that helped you accomplish your goal in two minutes and closed itself would be a commercial failure. The result is an arms race of engagement engineering — infinite scrolls, autoplay, streaks, notifications calibrated like slot machines — conducted by some of the most talented engineers alive, with your attention as the prize.

Economists note a revealing experiment: when researchers paid users to deactivate social media for a month, participants required surprisingly large payments — yet afterward reported being happier and continued using the platforms less. We appear to value these services highly while being made measurably worse off by our level of consumption. Free, it turns out, can be expensive.

None of this requires abandoning the free internet. It requires only an adjustment of posture: knowing the price you are actually paying, and asking — app by app, scroll by scroll — whether the trade is still worth it.`,
