    text: `A single teaspoon of healthy garden soil contains more living organisms than there are humans on Earth. The dirt beneath your feet — dismissed in everyday language as the very symbol of worthlessness — is among the densest, busiest, and least explored ecosystems on the planet.

The inventory strains belief. That teaspoon holds up to a billion bacteria from thousands of species, several meters of microscopic fungal filaments, thousands of protozoa, and dozens of nematodes, alongside mites, springtails, and insect larvae. Scientists estimate that a quarter of all species on Earth live in soil — and that the majority remain unnamed and unstudied. We have better maps of the surface of Mars than of the living architecture under an ordinary meadow.

The most remarkable resident may be the fungi. Mycorrhizal fungi weave through the ground and physically connect with plant roots, forming a genuine trading partnership: the plant supplies sugars produced by photosynthesis; the fungus, whose filaments reach where roots cannot, returns water and minerals. A single fungal network may link many trees simultaneously, and experiments with radioactive tracers have shown carbon flowing through fungal connections from tree to tree. Some researchers describe forests as cooperative systems wired together underground — a claim still debated, but grounded in real measurements.

This living machinery performs services civilization depends upon. Soil organisms decompose the dead and recycle their nutrients into new growth; without them, the planet would drown in its own debris within years. Soil stores more carbon than the atmosphere and all vegetation combined, making its health a quiet lever of climate stability. And nearly everything we eat begins there.

Yet we treat the system carelessly. Intensive plowing, chemical overuse, and erosion degrade soil far faster than nature rebuilds it — producing a centimeter of topsoil can take centuries.

Civilizations, the historian's warning goes, ultimately stand on their topsoil. It would be wise to remember that "dirt" is not dead matter to stand on, but a living inheritance to stand with.`,
