    text: `The acceptance letter arrives, the promotion is announced, the exam result exceeds every expectation — and instead of joy, a cold voice whispers: They made a mistake. You fooled them. Soon they will find out. If this voice is familiar, you belong to a remarkably large club that believes itself to have exactly one member.

Psychologists call the phenomenon impostor syndrome: the persistent inability to internalize one's own accomplishments, paired with the fear of being exposed as a fraud. First documented in the 1970s among high-achieving women, it has since been found across genders, professions, and cultures. By some estimates, the great majority of people experience it at some point — including, by their own admission, Nobel laureates, celebrated authors, and astronauts. Maya Angelou, after dozens of acclaimed books, confessed she still feared "they're going to find me out."

The syndrome has a perverse internal logic that makes it self-sustaining. Every success is reclassified to protect the fraudulent self-image: the exam was easy, the judges were lenient, it was luck, it was charm, anyone could have done it. Every failure, meanwhile, is admitted as direct evidence of the underlying truth. The accounting is rigged — credit is always deferred, blame always accepted — so no quantity of achievement can ever settle the question.

Part of the explanation lies in an asymmetry of information: you witness your own doubts, drafts, and panicked midnight revisions, but only the polished surfaces of everyone else. Comparing your inner chaos to others' outer composure, you reasonably conclude that you alone are improvising.

The most effective responses are disarmingly simple. Naming the pattern helps — a feeling labeled as a known cognitive distortion loses authority. Speaking it aloud helps more, since the response is usually a chorus of "you too?" And one reframe is supported by the evidence itself: genuine frauds rarely worry about being frauds. The anxiety is, ironically, a credential.

The voice may never fully disappear. But it can be demoted — from judge to background noise.`,
