    desc: "週末という制度の歴史を描く読み物。当たり前の起源を問う。",
    text: `The weekend feels like a law of nature — as fixed as the tides, as inevitable as sunrise. It is nothing of the kind. The two-day weekend is a recent human invention, younger than the telephone, and it was won, not given.

For most of history, the rhythm of rest was dictated by religion: one sacred day per week — Sunday for Christians, Saturday for Jews, Friday for Muslims — and even that day was less leisure than obligation. The industrial revolution then revealed how little rest custom actually guaranteed. Factory workers in the nineteenth century commonly labored ten to fourteen hours a day, six days a week. Children worked beside them.

The two-day weekend emerged from an unlikely alliance of pressures. Labor unions fought for shorter hours through strikes that were sometimes met with violence. In England, a curious tradition called "Saint Monday" — workers simply failing to appear after Sunday's recreations — convinced some employers that a legitimate half-Saturday would at least make absenteeism predictable. In the United States, the growing presence of Jewish workers, whose Sabbath fell on Saturday, gave factories a practical reason to close both days.

The decisive blow came from an unexpected direction: Henry Ford, no friend of unions, gave his workers the five-day week in 1926. His reasoning was nakedly commercial — workers with leisure time become customers; the man with a free Saturday buys an automobile and somewhere to drive it. Rest was good business. Within a decade and a half, the five-day week was law in America, and the pattern spread across the industrial world. Japan's government offices did not fully adopt two-day weekends until 1992 — within living memory of today's parents.

The history carries a quiet warning and an invitation. The warning: arrangements that feel eternal are merely agreements, and agreements can erode. The invitation: they can also be renegotiated. The four-day week now being trialed in several countries is not a utopian fantasy.

It is simply the next chapter of a story we forgot we were writing.`,
