    desc: "第一印象の形成速度とその信頼性を検証する心理読み物。",
    text: `Show someone an unfamiliar face for one-tenth of a second — barely longer than a camera flash — and they will confidently judge its owner's trustworthiness, competence, and likability. Give them five full minutes, and remarkably, their judgments barely change. They simply become more certain. The first impression is not the beginning of an evaluation; for most practical purposes, it is the verdict.

The speed reflects deep evolutionary machinery. For our ancestors, deciding within moments whether an approaching stranger meant cooperation or threat was a survival skill, and the brain regions involved — particularly the amygdala — operate faster than conscious thought. We do not decide to form impressions; they arrive pre-formed, and reasoning is dispatched afterward, mostly to justify them.

The disturbing part is what these instant judgments are based on: facial geometry that predicts nothing. Faces with features resembling expressions — upturned mouth corners suggesting a faint smile, prominent cheekbones — are reliably judged trustworthy; their owners receive better loan terms in experiments and lighter sentences in some courtroom studies. Faces rated as "competent-looking" have predicted election outcomes at rates far above chance, based on appearance alone. Adults with round "baby faces" are presumed innocent and warm; angular faces are presumed capable and cold. None of these judgments correlates meaningfully with actual character. We are, in effect, all phrenologists at first sight — reading personality from bone structure with great confidence and negligible accuracy.

The bias cannot be switched off; awareness does not prevent the impression from forming. But awareness changes what happens next. The skill worth cultivating is not the suppression of first impressions but their demotion: treating them as hypotheses rather than findings, deliberately gathering the disconfirming evidence that snap judgment never seeks, and building decision systems — structured interviews, blind auditions, anonymized review — that deny facial geometry its vote.

Orchestras learned this decades ago: when musicians began auditioning behind screens, the hiring of women rose dramatically.

The face is the loudest witness in the room — and frequently, the least reliable one.`,
