    desc: "光害が生態系と人間に与える影響を描く環境読み物。",
    text: `Two-thirds of humanity can no longer see the Milky Way. The galaxy we inhabit — the river of stars that guided navigators, inspired religions, and decorated every human night for two hundred thousand years — has been quietly erased from the sky above most of the species that once watched it. The eraser is our own light.

Light pollution is the least discussed of environmental problems, perhaps because it feels so benign. Light is safety, commerce, civilization; darkness is the ancient enemy. But the planet's life evolved under a strict rhythm of bright days and dark nights, and that rhythm is encoded deep in nearly every organism. Artificial light at night is not a neutral convenience. It is a continent-scale rewiring of a signal that biology treats as fundamental.

The ecological evidence has grown impossible to ignore. Newly hatched sea turtles, programmed to crawl toward the bright horizon of the sea, instead march inland toward beachfront lighting and die. Migrating birds, navigating by stars, circle illuminated buildings until they collapse from exhaustion; a single brightly lit structure can kill hundreds in a night. Insect populations — the foundation of countless food chains — are devastated by the lethal attraction of streetlights, a contributing factor in what entomologists call the global insect decline.

Humans are not exempt. The blue-rich light of screens and LED lamps suppresses melatonin, the hormone that orchestrates sleep, and large studies have linked sustained nighttime light exposure to sleep disorders and broader health concerns.

What makes light pollution unique among environmental problems is its reversibility. Carbon lingers for centuries; plastic for millennia. Light pollution ends at the flick of a switch. The solutions are almost embarrassingly simple: shielded fixtures that aim light downward where it is needed, warmer-colored bulbs, and the radical practice of turning things off.

A growing "dark sky" movement is creating protected reserves where the full night remains visible. Their argument is modest: the stars are not gone.

They are merely waiting behind a curtain we have the power to draw back.`,
