    desc: "テストという制度の長所と限界を考察する教育エッセイ。",
    text: `No technology shapes young lives more decisively than the examination. Tests determine schools, schools determine credentials, credentials open or close the doors of adulthood. Given these stakes, it is worth asking a question rarely posed inside the system itself: what do exams actually measure?

The honest answer is: something real, but less than we pretend. A well-constructed exam genuinely samples knowledge and certain skills — recall under constraint, structured reasoning, performance under pressure. These correlate, imperfectly, with valuable abilities. The trouble begins with everything the format cannot see. An exam cannot observe persistence across months, originality that needs time to ripen, the ability to collaborate, or the judgment to ask a better question than the one assigned. It measures the sprint and is silent about the marathon — yet life after school consists almost entirely of marathons.

Worse, any measurement that carries high stakes begins to distort the thing it measures. This is Goodhart's law: when a measure becomes a target, it ceases to be a good measure. Students, responding rationally to incentives, optimize for the test rather than the understanding it was meant to sample — memorizing model answers, mastering question-prediction, cramming material into fragile short-term storage that evaporates within weeks. Schools, judged by results, narrow teaching toward the examinable. The score rises; the learning it was supposed to represent quietly hollows out.

And yet the abolitionist's case collapses on inspection. The alternatives — interviews, recommendations, portfolios — are more easily distorted still, and distorted in a particular direction: toward the polished, the connected, the expensively coached. The blind, standardized exam, for all its bluntness, retains one democratic virtue no substitute has matched: it cannot see your surname, your accent, or your father's occupation. History records generations of poor students for whom a brutal exam was the only door that would open.

The mature position is uncomfortable but honest. Exams are a flawed instrument we keep because the alternatives are worse — a measure to be used, distrusted, and never confused with the human being holding the pencil.`,
