    desc: "タコの驚異的な知性を紹介する生物学読み物。異質な知能の形。",
    text: `If we ever wish to imagine how an intelligent alien might think, we need not look to the stars. A perfectly serviceable alien already lives in Earth's oceans, opening jars, solving mazes, and judging us through horizontal pupils. The octopus is the closest thing to a second, independent experiment in the evolution of minds.

The evolutionary distance is the crucial point. Our last common ancestor with the octopus lived perhaps six hundred million years ago and was likely a simple flattened worm with barely any brain at all. Every sophisticated feature of the octopus — its half-billion neurons, its problem-solving, its apparent curiosity — was assembled along a completely separate path from the one that produced mammals, birds, and us. Intelligence on Earth evolved at least twice, in unrelated lineages. Minds, it seems, are something the universe builds more than once.

And the octopus mind is built on a radically different plan. Two-thirds of its neurons reside not in its head but in its arms. Each arm processes information locally — touching, tasting, and deciding with substantial independence, while the central brain sets general intentions. A severed octopus arm can still reach and grasp. Researchers describe the animal, only half-jokingly, as a committee of nine intelligences loosely chaired by a central brain. What it feels like to be such a creature — whether its experience is unified or a chorus — is a question that keeps philosophers of mind awake at night.

The behavioral record is rich. Octopuses in laboratories distinguish individual human keepers, squirting water at ones they dislike. They unscrew jars from the inside, dismantle aquarium equipment, and escape through openings the width of their eyeball. Wild octopuses carry coconut shells across the seafloor to assemble as portable shelters — tool use of a sophistication once thought exclusive to vertebrates.

Then comes the melancholy twist: most octopuses live barely two years, and they die shortly after reproducing. All that cognition, dissolved almost as soon as it ripens — a brilliant mind built by evolution, used briefly, and discarded.

Intelligence, the octopus suggests, is not a ladder with humanity at the top. It is a sea, with many strange swimmers.`,
