    desc: "地図の歪みと政治性を解説する読み物。情報の見方を鍛える。",
    text: `Every flat map of the world is a lie. This is not an accusation but a mathematical theorem: a sphere cannot be flattened onto a plane without distortion, any more than an orange peel can be pressed flat without tearing. Every map must therefore choose which truths to sacrifice — and those choices, often invisible to the reader, shape how billions of people imagine the planet.

Consider the most familiar lie of all. The Mercator projection, designed in 1569 for ship navigation, preserves angles and directions — a genuine virtue for sailors — at the cost of catastrophic size distortion near the poles. On a Mercator map, Greenland appears equal to Africa; in reality, Africa is fourteen times larger. Europe swells; the equatorial world shrinks. Generations raised on classroom Mercators carry a quietly distorted mental globe in which the temperate north is grander than it is, and the tropical south smaller. Critics have long noted that this flattering enlargement of former colonial powers is, at minimum, an unfortunate coincidence.

The corrections breed their own controversies. Equal-area projections restore honest sizes while stretching shapes into unfamiliar distortions — and met fierce resistance precisely because accuracy looked "wrong" to eyes trained on the old lie. There is no neutral choice; every projection is an argument about what matters.

The distortions extend beyond geometry. Why does north sit at the top? No physical reason — it is pure convention; medieval Islamic maps placed south uppermost, and east-up maps gave us the word "orient." Why does your country sit at the center of your country's maps? Every nation prints itself into the middle of the world. Cartographers have even hidden deliberate fictions: "trap streets" — invented roads inserted to catch competitors who copy.

The lesson generalizes far beyond geography. A map is a model: a simplification built by someone, for some purpose, with something left out. So is a statistic, a news summary, a search result.

The question to carry everywhere is the cartographer's question: what did this picture have to distort in order to be drawn?`,
