    desc: "現代の孤独問題を公衆衛生の視点から考える読み物。",
    text: `In 2018, the United Kingdom appointed a Minister for Loneliness. Japan followed in 2021. The idea of a cabinet official for a private emotion struck many as strange — until they saw the data. Loneliness, public health researchers now argue, is not merely a sad feeling. It is a mortality risk comparable to smoking up to fifteen cigarettes a day, and it is spreading through wealthy societies like a slow epidemic.

The medical findings reframe the entire subject. Chronic loneliness is associated with elevated blood pressure, weakened immune response, disrupted sleep, accelerated cognitive decline, and significantly increased risk of early death. The mechanism appears rooted in evolution: for our ancestors, isolation from the group was lethal, so the body treats prolonged loneliness as an emergency — sustaining low-grade stress responses and inflammation that, maintained for years, corrode health. Loneliness, in this view, is the social equivalent of hunger: a biological alarm signaling an unmet survival need.

Crucially, loneliness is not solitude, and not a simple function of company. It is the subjective gap between the relationships one has and the relationships one needs. A person can be lonely in a crowded classroom or a busy family home — surrounded by contact, starved of connection. This explains the paradox of the hyper-connected present: the most digitally networked generations report the highest loneliness levels ever measured. Hundreds of online "friends" and a perpetual scroll of other people's highlight reels can coexist with — and by some evidence, worsen — the absence of a single person who truly knows you.

The modern epidemic has structural causes that no individual chose: people living alone in historic numbers, communities dispersed by job mobility, civic institutions in decline, town squares replaced by feeds.

The remedies, research suggests, are humbler than the problem sounds: regular, repeated, in-person contact; joining things — clubs, teams, choirs — where presence is expected; and the slow conversion of acquaintance into friendship through accumulated small encounters.

Connection, it turns out, behaves less like lightning and more like a garden. It grows where someone keeps showing up.`,
