    text: `The cup of coffee on the café counter costs about as much as a movie rental and is consumed in twenty minutes. Packed inside it, invisible, is one of the most revealing supply chains in the global economy — a chain connecting a farmer on a tropical hillside to your table through a journey that illuminates how the modern world actually works.

Coffee grows only in the "bean belt," the band of tropical highlands circling the equator, and it remains stubbornly resistant to mechanization: most of the world's coffee cherries are still picked by hand, one by one, at the moment of ripeness. An estimated hundred-plus million people, concentrated in some of the world's poorest regions, depend on the crop. Here the chain begins — and here, too, begins its central injustice. Of the price you pay for a café latte, the farmer who grew the beans typically receives a few percent. The great majority of the value is added — and captured — after the beans leave the farm: in shipping, roasting, branding, and the real estate and labor of the café itself. A sack of green beans that sustains a farming family for weeks becomes, in a wealthy capital, a single day's revenue for one espresso machine.

Farmers are exposed not only to this division of value but to its volatility. Coffee is traded on global commodity exchanges, where prices swing with weather in Brazil, currency movements, and speculation. A frost in one hemisphere doubles incomes in another; a bumper harvest somewhere can push prices below the cost of production everywhere.

Responses have multiplied: fair-trade certification guaranteeing price floors, direct-trade roasters bypassing middlemen, cooperatives giving small farmers collective bargaining power. Each helps; none has solved the fundamental arithmetic.

None of this is reason to abandon the morning ritual. It is reason to see it clearly. Globalization is not an abstraction debated on news programs. It is steaming, fragrant, and sitting in front of you — wealth and hardship dissolved together, in a cup that took a hundred hands to fill.`,
